:::summary
Adam Smith (1723–1790) was the Scottish moral philosopher and economist whose *The Wealth of Nations* (1776) founded the discipline of modern economics — demonstrating how free exchange, division of labor, and price signals coordinate the activity of millions of individuals to produce prosperity, and whose earlier *Theory of Moral Sentiments* (1759) grounded this economic vision in a Christian understanding of human nature, sympathy, and virtue.
:::

